{"parse":{"title":"Thaunkanhe (magazine)","pageid":32029113,"revid":810468912,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg/200px-Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"281\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg/300px-Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg/400px-Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"750\" data-file-height=\"1055\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Thaunkanhe_first_issue_cover.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Cover of the first issue of <i>Thaunkanhe</i> (May 1951, <a href=\"/wiki/Bachhala_(month)\" title=\"Bachhala (month)\">Bachhala</a> 1071 Nepal Sambat) showing woodblock illustration of Kathmandu Durbar Square.</div></div></div> <p><i><b>Thaunkanhe</b></i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Nepal_Bhasa_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nepal Bhasa language\">Nepal Bhasa</a>: <span lang=\"new\">\u0925\u094c\u0902\u0915\u0928\u094d\u0939\u0947</span>) is the first magazine in <a href=\"/wiki/Nepal_Bhasa\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nepal Bhasa\">Nepal Bhasa</a> to be published from <a href=\"/wiki/Nepal\" title=\"Nepal\">Nepal</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The monthly magazine began publication on 21 May 1951 (<a href=\"/wiki/Nepal_Era\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nepal Era\">Nepal Era</a> 1071 <a href=\"/wiki/Bachhala_(month)\" title=\"Bachhala (month)\">Bachhala</a>), coinciding with the festival of <a href=\"/wiki/Buddha%27s_Birthday\" title=\"Buddha&#39;s Birthday\">Swanya Punhi</a>, the \"full moon day of flowers\" marking the anniversary of the <a href=\"/wiki/Buddha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buddha\">Buddha</a>'s birth, enlightenment and <a href=\"/wiki/Nirvana\" title=\"Nirvana\">nirvana</a>. It was among the very few magazines published in Nepal at the time.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The first magazine in Nepal Bhasa was <i><a href=\"/wiki/Buddha_Dharma_wa_Nepal_Bhasa\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buddha Dharma wa Nepal Bhasa\">Buddha Dharma wa Nepal Bhasa</a></i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Devanagari\" title=\"Devanagari\">Devanagari</a>: \u092c\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927 \u0927\u0930\u094d\u092e \u0935 \u0928\u0946\u092a\u093e\u0932 \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e), which was published from <a href=\"/wiki/Kolkata\" title=\"Kolkata\">Kolkata</a>, India in 1925.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Honors\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Honors</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Thaunkanhe_(magazine)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Thaunkanhe</i> was started by former merchants <a href=\"/wiki/Purna_Kaji_Tamrakar\" title=\"Purna Kaji Tamrakar\">Purna Kaji Tamrakar</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Pushpa_Ratna_Sagar\" title=\"Pushpa Ratna Sagar\">Pushpa Ratna Sagar</a> and Ratna Man Singh <a href=\"/wiki/Tuladhar\" title=\"Tuladhar\">Tuladhar</a> with funds donated by <a href=\"/wiki/Lhasa_Newar_(trans-Himalayan_traders)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lhasa Newar (trans-Himalayan traders)\">Nepalese traders in Lhasa</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Tibet\" title=\"Tibet\">Tibet</a>. The three were its first editor, deputy editor and publisher respectively.\n</p><p>The monthly was registered at the Magistrate's Office, <a href=\"/wiki/Bhaktapur\" title=\"Bhaktapur\">Bhaktapur</a> and given Registered No. 12. It was published from 11/122 <a href=\"/wiki/Asan,_Kathmandu\" title=\"Asan, Kathmandu\">Asan</a> Tyouda, <a href=\"/wiki/Kathmandu\" title=\"Kathmandu\">Kathmandu</a> and printed at Bagiswar Chhapakhana, Jhochhen Laykusal, Kathmandu. From 1952, it was printed at Nepal Press, 11/122 Asan Tyouda, Kathmandu.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><i>Thaunkanhe</i> was launched two months after the Democratic Revolution in Nepal that toppled the <a href=\"/wiki/Rana_dynasty\" title=\"Rana dynasty\">Rana dynasty</a> and dismantled restrictions on private journalism.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The inaugural issue contained a message of felicitation from Minister of Industry and Commerce <a href=\"/wiki/Ganesh_Man_Singh\" title=\"Ganesh Man Singh\">Ganesh Man Singh</a>. Among the writers in the first issue were <a href=\"/wiki/Siddhicharan_Shrestha\" title=\"Siddhicharan Shrestha\">Siddhicharan Shrestha</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Chittadhar_Hridaya\" title=\"Chittadhar Hridaya\">Chittadhar Hridaya</a> and Hridaya Chandra Singh Pradhan.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>\"Thaunkanhe\" means \"nowadays\" in Nepal Bhasa. Its slogan, printed below the name on the front cover, is \"Progressive Monthly Magazine in Nepal Bhasa\". The contents consist of articles, essays, poems and news items. Its editorial policy championed the cause of <a href=\"/wiki/Linguistic_rights\" title=\"Linguistic rights\">linguistic rights</a> and inclusion of minority languages in the <a href=\"/wiki/Curriculum\" title=\"Curriculum\">curriculum</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Honors\">Honors</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Thaunkanhe_(magazine)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Honors\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Thaunkanhe</i> is the oldest Nepal Bhasa magazine still in print. Publication ceased in 1957 and resumed in 1992. On 5 March 2011, it was honored by the Nepal Literary Journalists Association for its contribution to journalism.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Thaunkanhe_(magazine)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Malla, Kamal Prakash (ed.) (1967). <i>Nahli Swana.</i> Kathmandu: Chwasa Pasa. Page 180.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Shresta, CB (1956). <i>Katmandu Guide.</i> Coronation Edition. Page 25.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">LeVine, Sarah and Gellner, David N. (2005) <i>Rebuilding Buddhism: The Theravada Movement in Twentieth-Century Nepal.</i> Harvard University Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-674-01908-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-674-01908-9\">978-0-674-01908-9</a>. Pages 27-28. Retrieved 10 August 2011.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Tuladhar, Kamal Ratna (22 March 2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ekantipur.com/the-kathmandu-post/2009/03/22/expression/a-man-of-letters/185728.html\">\"A man of letters\"</a>. <i>The Kathmandu Post</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">9 June</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Kathmandu+Post&amp;rft.atitle=A+man+of+letters&amp;rft.date=2009-03-22&amp;rft.aulast=Tuladhar&amp;rft.aufirst=Kamal+Ratna&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ekantipur.com%2Fthe-kathmandu-post%2F2009%2F03%2F22%2Fexpression%2Fa-man-of-letters%2F185728.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThaunkanhe+%28magazine%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://npi10month.blogspot.com/2010/02/history-of-nepali-journalism.html\">\"History of Nepali Journalism\"</a>. Nepal Press Institute. 15 February 2010<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">9 June</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=History+of+Nepali+Journalism&amp;rft.pub=Nepal+Press+Institute&amp;rft.date=2010-02-15&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnpi10month.blogspot.com%2F2010%2F02%2Fhistory-of-nepali-journalism.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThaunkanhe+%28magazine%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Thaunkanhe</i> (May 1951). Kathmandu: Ratna Man Singh.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=NLJA+conference&amp;NewsID=278963\">\"NLJA conference\"</a>. <i>The Himalayan Times</i>. 5 March 2011<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">13 June</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Himalayan+Times&amp;rft.atitle=NLJA+conference&amp;rft.date=2011-03-05&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thehimalayantimes.com%2FfullNews.php%3Fheadline%3DNLJA%2Bconference%26NewsID%3D278963&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThaunkanhe+%28magazine%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id